  "issue_number": 16,
  "issue_title": "ThreadInterruptShutdownHook hangs reload indefinitely when user's main() ignores interrupts",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\n`ThreadInterruptShutdownHook.hook()` calls `Thread.interrupt()` on the application's main thread and then `Thread.join()` with no timeout. If the user's `main()` is blocked on an operation that doesn't honour interrupts \u2014 `while (true) { \u2026 }` without an `isInterrupted()` check, `InputStream.read()` on a plain socket, an uninterruptible `synchronized` wait, a third-party loop that swallows `InterruptedException` \u2014 `join()` never returns. The entire reload pipeline blocks on that single hook call: `stopInternal()` doesn't progress, `startInternal()` for the new generation never runs, and every concurrent HTTP / gRPC request piles up behind the synchronized `reload()` waiting for the hook to finish.\n\nUser-visible symptom: edit a file \u2192 request hangs forever \u2192 the dev server looks frozen \u2192 the user kills it with Ctrl-C. From the outside this is indistinguishable from a deadlock and there's no log line explaining what's blocking.\n\n## Repro\n\nIn an sbt / mill / gradle project, write a `main` that does this:\n\n```scala\nobject App {\n  def main(args: Array[String]): Unit = {\n    // Common patterns that don't honour interrupts:\n    val server = new java.net.ServerSocket(8080)\n    while (true) {\n      val client = server.accept()  // InterruptedException? Never throws \u2014 accept() blocks on a syscall that ignores the interrupt flag on most JVMs/OSes.\n      client.close()\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nRun `liveReload`, send one request to boot the app, then edit a source file. The reload hangs forever in [`ThreadInterruptShutdownHook.hook()`](core/build-link/src/main/java/me/seroperson/reload/live/hook/ThreadInterruptShutdownHook.java).\n\nOther common shapes that hit this:\n\n- ZIO / cats-effect runtimes that catch `InterruptedException` and continue the fiber loop.\n- A Cask / http4s server whose own shutdown hook isn't wired up.\n- Any `Thread.sleep(Long.MAX_VALUE)` that catches and ignores `InterruptedException`.\n\n## Root cause\n\n`core/build-link/src/main/java/me/seroperson/reload/live/hook/ThreadInterruptShutdownHook.java`:\n\n```java\npublic void hook(Thread th, ClassLoader cl, DevServerSettings settings, BuildLogger logger) {\n  th.interrupt();\n  logger.debug(\"Waiting thread to finish\");\n  try {\n    th.join();         // \u2190 unbounded wait\n  } catch (InterruptedException ex) {\n    logger.error(\"Interrupted during join\", ex);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`join()` with no argument waits forever. `interrupt()` only sets a flag; it does not abort blocking syscalls that haven't been written to check the flag. The hook trusts that the user's code is interrupt-aware, but in practice most app code isn't.\n\n`BaseDevServerStart.runHooks()` propagates the hook's blocking semantics directly into `stopInternal()`, which holds the instance monitor \u2014 so every other request blocks behind it too.\n\n## Compatibility\n\n- New setting key has a safe default (5s) \u2014 no user action required.\n- No public API changes; the `Hook` interface signature is unchanged.\n- Plugin DSL is unchanged. Users who want a different timeout set it via `live.reload.thread.interrupt.timeout` in their `liveDevSettings` map (same pattern as other settings).\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n_No response_\n\n### Operating system\n\nLinux\n\n### Build System\n\nsbt\n\n### Version of jvm-live-reload\n\n0.1.1\n\n### JDK Version\n\n17.0.18\n\n### Extra context or search terms\n\n_No response_",
